            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this mortar calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This mortar calculator estimates the volume of mortar required
                and converts it into the number of preblended bags you should
                buy. It supports two main workflows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Brick / block wall mode</strong> – enter wall size and
                  unit dimensions; the tool estimates joint volume as a
                  percentage of the wall.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bed / slab mode</strong> – enter area and bed
                  thickness for paving, tile, or stone bedding layers.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Wall area and unit coverage</h3>
              <p>For a wall, the first step is to compute the wall area:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Wall area</strong> = wall length × wall height</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                From the brick or block dimensions, the calculator estimates how
                many units fit in one square foot (or square meter) of wall and
                shows this as
                <em>coverage per unit</em>. You can override this value if you
                have manufacturer data.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Estimating mortar volume in joints</h3>
              <p>
                Instead of trying to model every joint individually, a practical
                approach is to assume that mortar occupies a certain percentage
                of the wall volume. For brickwork, 15–25% is typical; for larger
                blocks, 10–20% is common.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Mortar volume (wall)</strong> ≈ wall area × joint
                  thickness × (mortar % ÷ 100)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator uses your <em>joint thickness</em> and
                <em>% of wall that is mortar</em> to estimate this volume.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Bed / slab mortar</h3>
              <p>
                For bedding layers under pavers, tiles, or stone, the
                calculation is more direct:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Mortar volume (bed)</strong> = area × bed thickness
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The tool converts thickness to feet or meters internally so that
                the volume is consistent with the bag yield units.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Converting volume to bags</h3>
              <p>
                Bagged mortar products specify an approximate yield per bag (for
                example, an 80&nbsp;lb bag might yield about 0.7&nbsp;ft³ of
                mixed mortar). Once the total mortar volume is known, the bag
                count is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Bags (no waste)</strong> = total mortar volume ÷ yield
                  per bag
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Bags (with waste)</strong> = Bags (no waste) × (1 +
                  waste % ÷ 100)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator shows both values so you can see the theoretical
                requirement and a more realistic number including waste and
                spillage.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical mortar mix ratios</h2>
              <p>
                When mixing mortar from separate cement, lime, and sand, common
                nominal volume ratios are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type N</strong>: 1 part cement : 1 part lime : 6 parts
                  sand
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type S</strong>: 2 parts cement : 1 part lime : 9
                  parts sand
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type O</strong>: 1 part cement : 2 parts lime : 9
                  parts sand
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Preblended bagged mortars already contain cement and sand in the
                correct proportions; you only add water. The
                <em>Mortar type</em> selector in this calculator is mainly for
                documentation and to remind you which mix you intend to use.
              </p>

              <h3>Recommended uses</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type N</strong> – general above-grade walls, exterior
                  and interior, non-load-bearing or moderate load.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type S</strong> – below-grade walls, retaining walls,
                  foundations, and higher-strength structural masonry.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Type O</strong> – low-strength interior work, historic
                  restoration, and soft masonry where a weaker mortar is
                  desirable.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Practical tips for ordering mortar</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Always round up</strong> – you rarely want to run out
                  of mortar mid-wall; extra bags store better than a cold joint.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check manufacturer datasheets</strong> – yields vary
                  between products; adjust the “yield per bag” field
                  accordingly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Account for workmanship</strong> – thicker joints,
                  irregular stone, and inexperienced crews all increase mortar
                  consumption.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider staging deliveries</strong> – on large jobs,
                  order an initial batch and then top up once you see actual
                  usage.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed for quick estimating. It assumes
                reasonably uniform units and joints, and does not model every
                head and bed joint individually. For critical structural work,
                always follow local building codes, manufacturer instructions,
                and consult with a qualified engineer or mason if in doubt.
              </p>
            </section>

